To prove $X$ is totally bounded pick $\epsilon > 0$. Consider $x_1 \in X$ and $B(x_1, \epsilon)$. If $B(x_1, \epsilon) = X$ we are done. Otherwise, $\exists x_2 \in X \backslash B(x_1, \epsilon)$ which implies $d(x_1, x_2) \geq \epsilon$. If $B(x_1, \epsilon) \bigcup B(x_2, \epsilon) \neq X$ $\exists x_3 \in X$ not in $B(X_1, \epsilon) \bigcup B(x_2, \epsilon)$. Assuming the procedure does not terminate, have $x_1, x_2, x_3, \ldots$ such that $d(x_i, x_j) \geq \epsilon$. Therefore, the sequence does not converge but this is a contradiction as every sequence must have a convergent subsequence. \\

$(3) \Rightarrow (2)$ Suppose $X$ is totally bounded and complete. Let $\{y_1, y_2, \ldots \}$ be a sequence in $X$. \underline{Claim}: If $X$ is totally bounded, then $\{y_n\}$ has a Cauchy subsequence. This would imply that the subsequence converges by completeness. \\
We construct a sequence of sequences in $X$ such that 
\begin{enumerate}
    \item $y_{1, n} = y_n$
    \item $\{y_{k, n}\}_{n = 1}^{\infty}$ is a subsequence of $\{y_{k-1}, n \}_{n =1}^{\infty}$
    \item $\{y_{k, n} \}_{n = 1}^{\infty}$ is contained in a ball of radius $\frac{1}{k}$ (some $B(x_k, \frac{1}{k})$
\end{enumerate}
By total boundedness, for $\epsilon = \frac{1}{k}$ $\exists x_k$ such that $B(x_k, \frac{1}{k})$ contains infinitely many terms. Take Cauchy sequence $y_{1, 1}, y_{2, 2}, y_{3, 3}, \ldots$. 
\[
y_{1, 1} \ y_{1, 2} \ y_{1, 3} \cdots
\]
\[
y_{2, 1} \ y_{2, 2} \ y_{2, 3} \cdots
\]
\[
y_{3, 1} \ y_{3, 2} \ y_{3, 3} \cdots
\]
\[
\vdots \ \vdots \ \vdots
\]


